[1] Malaysia (Selangor)
Date: Mon 31 Mar 2008
Source: Malaysia Star [edited]
<http://thestar.com.my/news/story.asp?file=/2008/3/31/nation/20080331135933>


On average there are 40 reported dengue cases daily in Selangor.

From January until 29 Mar 2008, Selangor reported 3743 cases. Of
that figure, 3550 cases of fever were recorded while there were 193
cases of DHF. Deaths suspected to be caused by the viral fever stood at 10.

Selangor Health, Estate Workers Affairs, Poverty Eradication and
Caring Government chairman Dr A. Xavier Jayakumar said the state is
concerned with the alarming number of cases being reported.

"Our immediate aim is to reduce the number of cases. In 2007 we had
32 deaths due to dengue-haemorrhagic fever and now we have 10
suspected deaths due to the viral fever," he said. He added that Shah
Alam city recorded 719 cases from January to 29 March [2008], the
highest in one locality.

"Shah Alam is a modern city, yet you have high statistics. Residents
might say not much is being done to clean up the area. But there
could be some truth to their statement. Again it also involves the
lackadaisical attitude and public's ignorance on how the disease is
spread," he said.

Xavier said construction sites, abandoned buildings, shop lots and
even schools are to be blamed for not checking on areas where water
collected and could be a breeding ground for mosquito larvae.

[Byline: Edward Rajendra]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED Rapporteur A-Lan Banks

[This is another illustration of the need for public participation in
elimination of _Aedes_ dengue virus vector mosquito breeding sites.

An interactive map of peninsular Malaysia showing the states and the
location of Shah Alam city, approximately 20 km SE of Kuala Lumpur,
can be accessed at:
<http://encarta.msn.com/map_701513676/kelang.html>. - Mod.TY]

