[5] Germany ex Maldives
Date: Wed 26 Mar 2008
From: Gerhard Dobler
<gerharddobler@bundeswehr.org>


Dengue Fever in a traveller returning from the Maldives.
------------------------------------------------------
A 49 year-old male German traveller who stayed for 10 days on the
Maldives fell ill one day after return to Germany (21 Mar 2008) with
fever (39.7C [103.46 F]), headache, and myalgia. He presented to an
emergency room and was treated with oseltamivir. On 25 Mar [2008] he
was referred to the Department of Tropical Medicine at University of
Munich showing fever, petechial bleeding of the gum, leucocytopenia
(2.800/mu l), and thrombocytopenia (70.000/mu l). A plasma sample was
tested at the Bundeswehr Institute of Microbiology and a positive
dengue real-time-RT-PCR and a negative chikungunya real-time-RT-PCR
were found. Typing of the causative dengue virus serotype is underway.

A dengue outbreak on the Maledives was reported in 2006 (ProMED
20060318.0834). This case of a returning traveller points to a
significant circulation of dengue virus on the Maldives in 2008 again.

--
Gerhard Dobler
Bundeswehr Institute of Microbiology
Munich, Germany
<gerharddobler@bundeswehr.org>

Pamela Perona, Thomas Lascher
Dept. of Infectious Diseases and Tropical Medicine
University of Munich, Germany

[ProMED thanks Drs. Dobler, Perona and Lascher for this 1st-hand
report. Of particular significance epidemiologically is their
observation that there is significant circulation of dengue virus on
the Maldives again in 2008.

A map of the Maldives showing ther location in the Indian Ocean, SE
of India, can be accessed at:
<http://www.worldatlas.com/webimage/countrys/asia/mv.htm>. - Mod.TY]

