[6] New Caledonia
Date: Mon 31 Mar 2008
Source: Pacific Magazine [edited]
<http://www.pacificmagazine.net/news/2008/03/31/dengue-fever-epidemic-continues-to-progress-in-new-caledonia>


Dengue fever cases in New Caledonia are continuing to soar with at
least 263 known cases since the beginning of this year [2008], the
local government said in a release on Friday [28 Mar 2008].

Oceania Flash reports that New Caledonia's dengue fever epidemic was
officially declared in February 2008.

Most of the known cases are concentrated in the capital Noumea and
its greater area, as well as other reported hotbeds in the
northeastern island of Lifou (part of the Loyalty group) and on the
Isle of Pines (South of the capital Noumea), local media report.

Health authorities in New Caledonia had [in] late February [2008]
upgraded the status of what was formerly a "pre-epidemic" situation
to a fully fledged "epidemic" with regards to dengue, mosquito-borne,
hemorrhagic fever.

In view of the apparent momentum of the epidemic, health minister
Sylvie Robineau has announced she will on Monday [31 Mar 2008] lead a
team of experts (including health and social affairs directors) to
visit the northeastern island of Lifou, which is part of the Loyalty
islands group.

The mission's objective is to assess the situation, but also to
reinforce the prevention message and measures with the local
population. The island is said to be one of the most severely
affected with 88 cases.

Robineau said the situation on Lifou was now a matter of urgency and
her government has moved to earmark special funds to purchase
mosquito repellents to be distributed to Lifou villagers free of
charge via rural health centres.

Since the outbreak of the epidemic in early February [2008], the
number of cases has steadily increased: there were only 72 cases at
the beginning of March, 165 cases mid-March and over 215 cases on 20 Mar 2008.

New Caledonia's health and prevention department is up in arms,
calling on the population to be more responsible in their efforts to
clean their own backyards from any potential mosquito breeding site
such as still water contained in old tyres and plant pots or any
bushy area on their compound that could also become a nest for mosquito larvae.

Health services have also stepped up their prevention and awareness
campaign against the potentially deadly virus.

They have once again stressed the situation is serious, mainly
because of the heavy rains and the hot and humid conditions currently
affecting New Caledonia.

As part of the prevention campaign, Noumea's health and hygiene
services have also deployed dozens of officers, whose main task is to
visit house and property owners and convince them to clean up.

An earlier dengue fever epidemic, in 2003, killed as many as 20
persons in New Caledonia.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promed.org>

[ProMED thanks rapporteur A-Lan Banks for sending in this same
article. A map of Oceania showing the location of New Caledonia in
