[7] Peru
Date: 09 - 15 Mar 2008
Source: Bol. Epidemiol. (Lima) 17 (11), 2008 [in Spanish, trans. &
summ. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://www.oge.sld.pe/Boletin_sem/2008/SE11/se11-01.pdf>


The Epidemiological Week (EW) 11 [09-15 Mar 2008], the Regional
Directorate of Health (DIRESA) reported 216 cases of classical dengue
fever to the Department of Epidemiology (EDM), 85 percent of the
cases were reported by: Loreto (49 percent) Lambayeque (16 percent),
Ucayali (8 percent), Amazon (7 percent).and Luciano Castillo (5
percent). To date 14 health directorates have provided notification
of confirmed [dengue] cases.

Up through EW 11 (2008) 3840 dengue cases have been reported to the
OGE (General Epidemiology Office), of which 622 cases have been
confirmed by laboratory test (IgM ELISA).

As for cases of DHF, 3 cases have been confirmed this week; none
died. The cumulative incidence [of DHF] in the country through EW 11
is 13.80 cases per 100 000 inhabitants. The Departments [state of
province equivalents] with the highest incidence are: Loreto
(220.49), Ucayali (95.96), St. Maarten (32.28), Lima (26.15) Madre de
Dios (13.84), La Libertad (21.18), Jaen (17.06) and Amazon (46.34).
The departments that were experiencing [dengue] outbreaks in EW 11
are: Loreto, Lambayeque, Amazon and Piura II.

The Loreto DIRESA notes a trend of decline in the number of [dengue]
cases. Motupe, and Olmos and Bagua initiated actions for the control
of outbreaks.

--
Communicated by:
Juan Carlos Celis Salinas
Infectious Diseases Physician
Peruvian Research Group for Infectious and Tropical Diseases
<charapa3@yahoo.com, dr_jcelis@gipeit.com>

