[8] Brazil (Amazonas)
Date: Fri 14 Mar 2008
Source: Portal Amazon [in Portuguese, trans. & summ. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://portalamazonia.globo.com:80/noticias.php?idN=65170&idLingua=1>


In 2008 2 children died of DHF; these cases are under investigation.
The information is from the Director-Chairman of the Foundation for
Surveillance in Health (SVM), Evandro Melo. This number is equal to
[the number of fatal DHF cases] registered during the entire year of 2007.

According to Melo, the deaths occurred in children of 7 years [of
age]. The cases were registered in the first 2 months of the year
[Jan / Feb 2008]. According to the records of SVM, children who died
were living in Manaus and there have been no suspected [dengue]
deaths in the interior of the state.

Data on the disease recorded by the state Secretary of Health will be
released today [14 Mar 2008] on the balance sheet of the operation
"Impact" to combat dengue. The operation began 2 weeks ago and is
being carried out in partnership with the fire brigade and the armed forces.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-PORT
<promed@promedmail.org>

[In response to a report that dengue virus 4 (DEN - 4) was
circulating in Manaus, Dr. Pedro Tauil, a respected Brazilian
virologist, wrote to ProMED-PORT as follows: It is very strange that,
having a population completely non-immune to DEN-4 [virus], this
virus has not generated a great epidemic and also, since then
(October 2007) was not detected any more. Additionally, the national
reference laboratories, the Institute Evandro Chagas and Fiocruz
[Oswaldo Cruz Foundation], have not confirmed this positive [DEN-4
result] in samples [they] examined. - Mod.JW]

[The Adjunct Secretary of Health Surveillance of the Brazilian
Ministry of Health, Fabiano Pimenta, on 27 Mar 2008 officially
rejected the report that DEN-4 virus had entered Brazil. The agent in
question was DEN-3 virus, not DEN-4 virus. However, he considers that
the entry of DEN-4 virus in Brazil is inevitable, considering that it
is circulating in neighboring countries, such as Venezuela, Ecuador
and Honduras. His comments were reported in UOL Ciencias e Saude [in
Portuguese]
<http://cienciaesaude.uol.com.br/ultnot/estado/2008/03/27/ult4513u934.jhtm>.

A map of Brazil showing the states including Amazonas can be accessed at:
<http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/americas/brazil.jpg>. - Mod.TY]

